NFSv4 Migration and Hardening (Recommended Alternative Solution): To permanently eliminate the need for rpcbind and comply with CIS benchmarks, transition the application to NFSv4 and apply the following hardening measures:
Protocol Enforcement: Explicitly disable legacy NFSv2 and NFSv3 via the Service Management Facility (SMF). Use sharectl set -p server_versmin=4 nfs and sharectl set -p server_versmax=4 nfs.
Strong Authentication (Kerberos): Deprecate sys (AUTH_SYS), which is highly vulnerable to UID/GID spoofing. Enforce Kerberos authentication. Use sec=krb5 for secure authentication, sec=krb5i for data integrity, or sec=krb5p for full data-in-transit encryption.
Strict Export Controls: Restrict NFS shares strictly to authorized client IP addresses or subnets using ZFS share properties (e.g., zfs set share.nfs.sec.default.rw=<IP> <pool/dataset>). Never export to * or broad subnets.
Privilege Restriction: Ensure root squashing is enforced (map root access to an unprivileged anonymous UID) to prevent clients from exercising administrative privileges on the mounted share.



































